; d3d12_proxy_forwarding.def.example
;
; A real drop-in d3d12.dll proxy needs to forward ALL exports to the
; original DLL (renamed to d3d12_orig.dll). Otherwise, games and tools
; that call any unforwarded D3D12 function will crash before useful
; capture occurs.
;
; This .def file should be generated from the real d3d12.dll export table
; using: dumpbin /exports d3d12.dll  (MSVC) or: objdump -p d3d12.dll (MinGW)
;
; Pattern: every export forwards to d3d12_orig.dll EXCEPT D3D12CreateDevice,
; which is intercepted by the hook DLL.
;
; Generated from: Windows 10/11 d3d12.dll (export list varies by Windows version)
; The list below is illustrative — generate your own from your target OS.

LIBRARY d3d12_proxy

EXPORTS

; === Intercepted by our hook ===
D3D12CreateDevice = D3D12CreateDevice

; === Forwarded to the original d3d12.dll (rename to d3d12_orig.dll) ===
D3D12GetDebugInterface = d3d12_orig.D3D12GetDebugInterface
D3D12EnableExperimentalFeatures = d3d12_orig.D3D12EnableExperimentalFeatures
D3D12GetInterface = d3d12_orig.D3D12GetInterface
D3D12SerializeRootSignature = d3d12_orig.D3D12SerializeRootSignature
D3D12SerializeVersionedRootSignature = d3d12_orig.D3D12SerializeVersionedRootSignature

; NOTE: The actual d3d12.dll on Windows 10 1903+ exports only 5-7 functions.
; The full COM interface is obtained via D3D12CreateDevice and does not
; need separate exports. However, if your target application loads
; d3d12.dll dynamically and calls GetProcAddress for any of these,
; the forwarding must cover them.

; === For maximum compatibility, generate from your specific d3d12.dll ===
; Run this on a Windows machine with the target d3d12.dll:
;   dumpbin /exports C:\Windows\System32\d3d12.dll > d3d12_exports.txt
; Then convert each line to:  ExportName = d3d12_orig.ExportName
; EXCEPT for D3D12CreateDevice which stays as our hook.
